Patient received COVID vaccine approximately one week prior to admission.  Patient developed acute rhabdomyolysis requiring hospitalization.  She developed pain and stiffness in her neck which spread to her back and generalized muscles to the point where she had difficulty moving in the next 12 hours.  She did not have difficulty swallowing but she did have difficulty chewing and complained of throat pain.  Upon arrival to the emergency room she was unable to lift her legs to get out of the car.  In the emergency room she was found to have a CK of 130,000 along with a creatinine of 1.1 and potassium of 6.8 with a calcium of 7.0.  She was admitted to the hospital ward and given aggressive IVFs. The following am she was having trouble breathing and was started on BIPAP; the repeat CK level climbed to 543,500.  She continued to worsen, developing increased swelling around the mouth and neck.  She became anuric with acute kidney injury; and was subsequently transferred to CCC upon which she was intubated and initiated on CRRT.
LAB_DATA: ABG showed pH of 7.15 and lactic acid of 2.7 mmol/L.  CK level peaked at 744,000.  CT scan suggested myositis in her masseter muscles but gluteal muscles could not be well viewed. A repeat CXR showed a progressive right pleural effusion.  Other laboratories included elevated LFTs (ALT 2694 and ALT 10,885) and mild hypocomplementemia.  BUN/SCr worsened to 42/4.1.

Other than perhaps a touch of fatigue, some mild soreness only at the injection site (left arm), and mild shoulder joint pain, I had no notable reaction to my first Moderna vaccine (April 20, 2021; Moderna Lot #047B21A).   On the evening of the day I received the second Moderna vaccine (injection around noon on May 18, 2021; Moderna Lot #017C21A) I experienced chills, fatigue, significant muscle aches (especially in entire left arm, shoulder, neck, and very significantly in my legs), as well as joint pain. The following day, May 19, the fatigue grew much worse, and the muscle aches and joint pain continued, but the chills subsided. The following day, May 20, an approximately 3" x 6" swath of my upper left arm began to painfully swell and was VERY hot to the touch; visually, it was very slightly red but not dramatically so. I was still fatigued and achey, with some joint pain. By today, May 21, the area remains very painful and weirdly hot to the touch, and in addition *has turned a bright angry red color*. The hot, swollen area begins exactly 4" below the injection site, as measured from the edge of the bandaid to the edge of the affected area. As the skin reaction grows worse, my other symptoms have improved. Other than the skin reaction, I have mild fatigue and very mild aches and joint pain.
LAB_DATA: None. I am away from home visiting an elderly relative who has been unwell with an age-related issue.
ALLERGIES: Very mild latex allergy (latex gloves cause back of hands to itch); mild birch allergy.

On 10-APR-2021, within 30 minutes of vaccination, the patient developed anaphylaxis with no airway compromise, hives, swelling of limbs, face and administration site. The outcome of the sore arms, fatigue, foggy headed, myalgia, arthralgia, shortness of breath, difficulty walking across the room/unsteady gait, extreme vertigo, diarrhea, weak legs, fever, headache/occipital headache, loss of peripheral vision, anaphylaxis, numb legs, suspicion of fluid leak into ears and decreased lung function was not reported. SYMPTOM_TEXT: -Face tingly and/or numb starting with lips before spreading to entire face about 40 minutes after injection. Felt like face was going in and out of conscienceness entire time. Sometimes felt like the sensation when a scab on a scrape is healing and the new skin is forming under the scab. Based on internet research with others having this rare side effect wanted to note that there was no swelling or change in heart rate (also I have not had any cosmetic surgery). But most reactions tended to be after the second dose and not the first as in my case. This mainly lasted about 48 hours at a pain level of medium with occasional minor occurrences after that. -Left bicep soreness (entire bicep not localized to injection). Pain intensified when touched or arm lifted above head. Pain level medium but consistent. Started about 16 hours after injection and last about 60 hours. - Overall body soreness. Felt like being hit by a freight train. Pain level fairly high starting about 18 hours after injection and lasting about 24 hours gradually decreasing in pain level over duration of that period. - About 40 hours after injection, face felt like it was hit by a frying pan, most pain localized to where nose meets face (not tip of nose) and radiated out from the bones around the nose to the rest of the face. These symptoms were high pain level for 36 hours and probably a low pain level about 24 hours after that. - About 70 hours after injection, dizziness and headache lasting for about 8 hours. Medium pain level. - Almost all high and medium level side effects are finally gone after 4 days although still minor face pain and left arm bicep pain exist.  (Sorry I didn't know I could report side effects so have been trying to keep track on paper as best as I could this week).

Abnormal fatigue lasts approximately 72 hours. Left arm is, of course, very sore at site of injection for approximately 36 hours.  Treatment: rest and hydration (Gatorade & water). My primary dr but I received vaccines via CVS.     4/2nd 1st vaccine: nausea, light headache & extreme fatigue. I fell asleep several hrs after I got it & was fatigued the next day. Additionally, began to feel jittery/clumsy w/ my fingers, eye twitching, some shooting pains on the legs, some vertigo. The jitters stayed for about a wk or so, eye twitching was bad & I felt a little anxiety ridden/panic attack like. After 4 wks passed, eye twitching had lessened, vision kept changing thruout this time & jitters seemed to be gone. Interesting, I had not had a menstrual cycle in many months but had one 3 - 4 weeks after vaccine.     5/2nd 2nd vaccine: I was a little tired the 1st day. Two days later, I was hit with fatigue, jitters, eye twitching too but lighter version. Along w/fatigue, I didn't feel like myself & felt anxious & short.  I started to have internal vibrations/shaking of tingling toes/fingers/abdomen/vaginal area - light burning too. Recently, a little on my left shoulder. As well, I had some highly infrequent but sharp, painful aching pains in foot area. Last 3 days I feel like my energy is up again, like myself. Vibrations & eye/vision issues continue though not as bad. I hope it all resolves and I continued in this better state.  I do hope to get back to 100% though.  This has all been concerning.
LAB_DATA: None.  Only better now to be able to begin to report.  Will follow up on lingering issues with my primary, and long term oncologist.
HISTORY: Breast Cancer and Breast Implant Illness survivor.

She got her vaccine and within 10 minutes she felt like her heart did a big woosh and was sitting with her husband and told him that it was hitting her blood stream as she had not had the reaction since starting some medication due to lupus.  The first hour it was fairly overwhelming wooshing sensation that made her feel uncomfortable and restless, and then got less.  Over the course of the week it continued to happen and did not feel right.  She called her PCP and by the time she got to see him  on 5/20/21 it had been a month, but had not worsened to go to the ER.  She had an EKG that showed acquired long QT syndrome, and told her that she could not get the 2nd vaccine.   He said that if she got hte 2nd vaccine that there was a likelihood that she would develop Torsades de pointes and that it could be life threatening.  Now he has to be careful on what to treat her due to this condition.   He told her to take really good care of herself and to continue take her medications and if it got worse to go to the ER.  She will FU with him in a month and he would continue to check EKG's to see if it will go away or not.   She is more tired and if she goes up and down the steps she is out of breath much quicker than before this condition.  She had several  normal EKG's in the past that he compared the last one with and she did not have this condition on previous EKG's.    She wishes that they would put out information for people who have autoimmune issues to publish these reactions to be watchful of reactions.  Feels they need to update the website to report similar side effects.
HISTORY: Systemic lupus and fibromyalgia, IBS, thyroid disease.
ALLERGIES: Penicillin and all derivatives, Sulfa, Quinalone family drugs, Naproxen.

LAB_DATA: Clinically presented with findings concerning for myopericarditis.   Trop 1900 -> 1600 -> 1300.  CK MB 42 -> 5.1  CRP 90 -> 83 -> 17.  ESR 40 -> 34 -> 44.   Infectious work up negative.  Autoimmune work up negative.   Cardiac MRI: Cardiac MRI findings of moderately reduced left ventricular systolic function. There is significant subepicardial enhancement on early gadolinium and late gadolinium imaging of the lateral, inferior and anterior wall of the left ventricle and free wall of the right ventricle. The native T2 is elevated at 63 ms consistent with myocardial edema. There is mild pericardial thickening with small pericardial effusion and patchy areas of enhancement. Findings are consistent with acute myopericarditis

I wanted to report this as a possible correlation between the building of Covid antibodies/immune cells and depletion of glucose in type 1 diabetes. Thank you.

The day after the first shot, my mother had bad knee pain in her left knee. It went on for days/week. After the second dose, days out she started feel very tired and bad pain in her feet that went to her hands and she couldn't get out of bed or urinate properly. Her facility doctor gave her Gabepentin for the pain but it did not help. She declined over a week or so and then She was admitted into the hospital for dehydration (March 19, 2021). The put a catheter in her to get urine out and bring her kidney function back to her normal (she does have kidney disease). Gave her more Gabepentin (which does not help pain in feet an hands) and released her to rehab. and she is now on oxygen.  Rehab was bad so I got her out and released to her facility so she could receive rehab there. She declined again with the same reaction: extreme fatigue, can't walk and now urinates and defecates in an adult diaper and now breathing is very labored.  She was admitted to the hospital and they can't find out why she is in this way. They did blood work, tests, scan and X-rays without any answers. They switched up meds on her and then released her to rehab since she hasn't walked in weeks/month at this point. She is regaining strength but now on oxygen even when sitting. She is 86 and walked with a walker all around her facility and when going to doctor appointments. Now she is in a wheelchair for doctor appointments since she has no strength and needs oxygen to walk. Her facility saw her decline after the second shot and my mom is very vocal and each day told them how she felt awful and it is because of the shot. She still has neuropathy in her feet and hands but it is not as painful as it originally was and it peaked and now just painful about a 5-6 on a scale of 0-10.
LAB_DATA: March 19, 2021 first hospital stay. Many tests done. Second hospital stay and more tests done.
OTHER_MEDS: 2 high blood pressure meds, furosemide, vitamin C, montelukast, pepcid, hydroxurea, Zoloft, busbar, another anxiety med, levothyroxine

4 days after first shot, she called me complaining of bad back pain. She was going to her family doctor the next day for her 21 yr old well visit and was going to get it checked out then. She had a complete physical and was cleared even her lungs were clear and she was good. Tuesday night April 13th at  10pm, she told me she had "air bubbles" in her chest. I said you mean indigestion, take tums I said. She said not mom, actual air bubbles and they are popping in my chest. I said you just got your physical, you are fine. They Thursday night April 15th she started having difficulty breathing and was out of breath. She went to urgent care on April 16th because she felt awful and they saw in an X-ray that she had a "cyst" in her upper right part of her lung and her lung was about to collapse. Sent her home on bed rest with a stereos and 2 inhalers. We got her Friday night from college because the pain in her back and now her chest was worse. Took her to ER and she had a collared lung and pneuomothroax. She was admitted to the hospital and they tried to see if the lung would heal itself.  It did not. They had to do surgery to repair the hole. When they were in there they saw a cobblestone texture where the hole was an they removed that texture and repaired the hole. She has never had a lung issue. Ever. She is also the 3rd person in my family to have had an adverse reaction to the shot. 6 of us vaccinated and 3 with injuries.

Beginning 5/15/2021 at 2pm, she experienced a fever that was not relieved by OTC medications, genital itching, burning, and pain.  She noticed blood when wiping after urinating at 8pm.  She also noticed "sores, blisters" on the vulva.  She went to the ER for evaluation at 6am 5/16/2021 and was treated with antiviral medication (Acyclovir PO).   In the afternoon of 5/16/2021 highest fever recorded was 102.6.   High fever associated with uncontrollable shivering.  Took Tylenol and Advil rotating every 3hrs and fever finally dropped to 99.0.    On 5/17/2021 she was put on an infusion of Acyclovir every 8hrs (outpatient).    Sores on vulva became progressively larger and the vulva was swollen and hard.  On 5/18/2021, no improvements were noted and fevers continued every afternoon.  On 5/19/2021 She saw Dr.  for further evaluation.  She was diagnosed with a secondary infection and it was decided by the doctor that she was being treated with the wrong medication.  The doctor decided her sores resembled Lipschutz ulcers. Her infusions of Acyclovir were discontinued and she was placed on Vancomycin and steroid infusions  every 12hrs.  She was also prescribed lidocaine ointment for pain relief.  The fevers resolved after the first infusion of Vancomycin and steroids.  On 5/20/2021, the sores stopped growing.  On 5/21/2021 the swelling has decreased, vulva is softening and the pain is 5/10.  She saw Dr.  again today and was taken off the Vancomycin and put on PO Bactrim for 7 days.  She has two more steroid infusions.  She will then switch to oral steroids and gradually wean off of them.  She will f/u with Dr. on 5/27/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was seen for a covid-19 vaccine. (Front Staff) then called the Mom,  to clarify the date of birth of patient.  Mom stated they lied about her daughter?s date of birth and made a parental decision to have her daughter get the vaccine early and changed her birthday, her actual DOB . We were also advised to enter the vaccine into MCIR and fill out a VAERS form.  The VAERS form was submitted on 5/21/2021. She asked if the patient would have to restart the vaccine.  I advised her I cannot answer that because she does not fall into the guidelines and would have to reach out to the county and I provided her with the number to reach County Covid-19.  At this time there are no adverse reactions to report.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About two to three  weeks after my second vaccination I woke up with a broken blood vessel in my left eye on the inside corner.  I looked it up and saw it was nothing serious. She checked me thoroughly and asked if I had taken ibuprofen recently. I had, twice in the last week for muscle soreness. She said she believed that was the cause and not to worry. The bruise went away the same week which was last week. I have taken ibuprofen for decades without any side effects. Today I saw my ex husband and same thing...he had a broken blood vessel in the inner corner of his eye! Again never happened before. Common denominators...we both had the Pyser vaccine, we both took ibuprofen weeks or months after...he?s a doctor so he was vaccinated a few months before me....the point being it?s very  odd it happened to both of us. He did have Covid in November of 2020. I have not gotten it luckily. I am reporting these occurrences because you need to do the math with all the information we can provide you with. Thank you for your time and attention to this matter.

Patient presented for 2nd dose of Pfizer vaccine.  RN was the nurse to administer the vaccine.  Prior to administering the vaccine, she began the documentation.  That is when a warning popped up saying the patient had already received maximum doses of vaccine.  RN excused herself and found the clinic lead.  I queried the patient and noted that she received Pfizer vaccine on 3/16/21, 4/6/21, and 4/30/21.    I asked the patient if she received a first and second dose, and she responded "yes".  I asked if she received a 3rd dose with us and she responded "yes".  I asked if she was wanting a 4th dose of vaccine today, and she responded "yes".  I educated the patient that she was considered fully vaccinated after 2 doses of the vaccine and that she didn't not need any further doses.  She responded that she is immunocompromised and wants to receive more than 2 doses.  She understands in other countries they are giving 3rd and 4th doses to patients similar to herself.  I explained that in this country, we are only authorized to give 2 doses 3 weeks apart and that I would not be giving her another dose today.  I told her I would need to report this error.  She asked if she had just gotten us in trouble, to which I responded "no".  I also reassured her that she was not in any trouble, but that she shouldn't continue to seek more vaccines.  At this point she shared that she works at a university and the first 2 COVID cases on campus occurred in the lab that she works.  Next week, things on campus are "going back to normal" and she is nervous.  I told her that it's ok to be nervous and scared, especially after everything we've been through in the last year.  I reassured her that she is fully vaccinated and that she can continue to wear her mask (she had on 3) as long as she felt comfortable.  I reiterated that I would not be administering a 4th dose of vaccine today, and she verbalized that she understood and left with her driver.  Throughout the entire encounter, she was very calm and forthcoming.  I contacted department head and discussed the situation.  She advised me to complete a VAERS report, which I will do.  The patient didn't report any adverse side effects to her 3rd dose.

From Monday, 5/10/21 to current date, 5/21/2021, I have been more active in doing housework, outdoor projects, I've been mentally able to focus on things (like meal planning, creating grocery lists) and carry them out (getting groceries and cooking regular meals). These are normal things people do every day but my depression and ADD affect my ability to do so. It occurred to me yesterday, 5/20, the only thing that has happened differently, that could be the reason for the "new" me is the vaccine. I posted to social media about what I've written above and I actually had two other people say they had the same reactions: one person said they felt the same way after the second shot and "it was like all my worries were gone and almost as high feeling" and another person said "Both my mom and I had the same...with Pfizer....both had this hard to describe feeling of agitation, like we couldn't sit still. I was exceedingly productive after both shots!" Since I wasn't the only one that had these "side effects", I thought it was worth reporting since people only seem to report the bad. As of today, 5/21/21, I have not "recovered" and I hope I don't!

Began with soreness in the arm at the site of the injection, several hours after the vaccine was administered. Progressed around 4PM to slight fatigue, headache whenever head was moved too quickly. Fatigue and headache worsened to the point that I took Acetominophen to counteract the headache at 9 PM. Went to bed at 10 PM Felt overheated during the night, but slept decently until I felt the need to urinate at ~4AM. Fell back into a half-sleep until 8AM or so. Performed my daily exercise routine (40 decline pushups, 40 pushups, 40 incline pushups, 50 situps, and 50 unweighted squats), noticed overheating more easily than normal, considerable fatigue, and headache whenever moving the head too rapidly. Had temperature taken midway through, 99 degrees Fahrenheit. Took Acetominophen for the headache around 9:30 AM. Experienced intense fatigue over the course of the day, general feeling of being overheated, and headache persisted, but felt no need for medication. Also found intense soreness in the arms (probably related to my exercise routine which involves 120 pushups altogether?) Went to bed at 10 PM. Again, woke up to relieve bladder at ~4 AM then fell back asleep. In the morning, fatigue lifted, still have a general feeling of being too warm, headache has lessened to only when I raise my voice, soreness in arms persists.
PRIOR_VAX: Intense soreness at site of injection

12 yo male presenting with bilateral lower extremity paresthesias and confusion.  Admitted to the hospital.  Pending discharge to rehab facility.  ED Note 5/19/21 Patient is a 12-year-old male with hypogammaglobulinemia, asthma, IBS who presents with weakness in his lower extremities.   6 days ago, patient had seafood and later that night vomited once, nonbloody, nonbilious. 4 days ago, he received the first dose of the Pfizer SARS-CoV2 vaccination. That day, he also felt some burning over the anterior parts of his bilateral ankles. Over the past 3 days, he has been sleeping a lot and had a headache. He has not had a fever or other muscle aches, no subsequent N/V, abdominal pain. Last night, he reported ankle pain to his mom. Today at school, he was playing kickball when he had the sensation that his ankles were not working/gave out and he fell to the ground. He had difficulty getting up and required a wheelchair. He did not lose consciousness, denied CP, palpitations, SOB, headache, vision change during or before that episode. He was not incontinent of urine/stool and had no abnormal movements noted at the time. Since then he has noted twitching in his thighs, calves and toes. He reports weakness throughout both lower extremities and has difficulty with intentional movements at the toes/ankles/knees, weakness in hips. He reports a burning sensation over the anterior ankles/dorsum of foot b/l. Denies fevers, chills, cough, SOB, CP, palpitations, abdominal pain, N/V/C. He endorses diarrhea 3x daily which is his baseline. He has panic attacks 3x daily w palpitations/SOB that self resolve. He has been on keflex for an ingrown toe nail for the last week.  MRI performed with normal brain and spine.  However, on repeat exam patient has diminished sensation in the bilateral feet and diminished ability to dorsiflex or plantarflex both ankles with very limited toe range of motion.  Still with preserved reflexes in the patella and Achilles.  Discussed at length with neurology and the family.  Differential diagnosis at this point of functional neurological disorder versus Guillaine Barr� syndrome.   Neurology note 5/21/21 Patient is a 12yo M with hypogammaglobinemia, IBS, and poorly controlled anxiety, presenting with 4 days of lower extremity paresthesias and 1 day of hyperacute onset of lower extremity weakness and perhaps some mild confusion.   History notable for covid vaccine three days prior to presentation and anixety surrounding covid and return to school. His general examination is notable for anxious affect with difficult to localize neurologic exam. Exam shows possible bilateral lower extremity weakness of TA and hamstring>quad/IP that is very challenging to grade due to poor effort and giveway, and decreased sensation in a bilateral stocking/glove distribution to all sensory modalities.  MRI w/wo contrast brain and spinal cord normal on admission. LP perfromed in ED also normal. Given negative workup and history of anxiety with recent psychosocial stressors, most likely sudden onset weakness is secondary to a functional neurologic disorder.  Plan for discharge to rehab pending PT evaluation.
LAB_DATA: MRI brain/spine - normal LP - normal, culture gram stain - neg; varicella-zoster PCR - neg COVID neg

started as severe dizziness and weakness, chest pain was hospitalized once I got to the ER because my heart was not working properly, after many test the found my heart was in heart failure with an output of 35% only, was in hospital for 5 days. Doctors couldn't see what caused such a sudden weakness of the heart, they did cardio path and arteries have zero blockage, they did ECO, and a EP Study. My heart now suffers from PVCs or arrhythmia and they are very irregular and frequent. Was given medicine to help the heart and control the PVCs, and discharged with wearing a safety vest, to follow up with the cardio doctors. Followed up with doctors and they have done an MRI which shows scarring of the heart. The doctor has determined that the diagnosis is myocardiatis. There is no proof this direct relation with the vaccine,  however symptoms started soon after the vaccine in a healthy young man. Now I still have to go to another electrophysiologist to see what he can do to help alleviate the PVCs and continue to take the medication to see of the heart can improve. I could not work for a month, and still cannot resume normal activities because my heart is to weak to sustain it.

She got her vaccine, no pain, not even a red mark on the arm.  She was to stay 30 minutes due to her immune issues, and she immediately felt like a ripple of a headache from the top of her forehead going all the way back and down her head.  She waited 25 minutes and went home.  She laid down and the headache never went pounding until the next morning.  She was weak and tired on Wednesday.  That night she saw the red infection around her left leg.  She was laying down and her hand dropped to her leg and at the top of her left thigh she looked at it and it looked like a wide ribbon that went all the way around the leg was pinkish red.  Then she went to sleep and when she woke up at 4:30 she almost fell.  She sat back on her bed as she was dizzy and from then on was dizzy upon sitting or standing and had to take her time.  She then couldn't turn to the left or right without spinning out and falling.   At the same time she was talking to people who stated that she was weird sounding and that she was not on the topic they were discussing, and she started calling her several times a day to check on her.   She had red eyes and conjunctivitis.  On Friday morning her friend came over to check on her and told her that she didn't look good and took her to the ER.  She could barely walk and took her to the ER and as she started to walk they told the ER that she needed a wheelchair and had to put her stuff on a conveyer belt and put her in a wheelchair.  He took her to the unit due to her adverse reaction to the vaccine.  She was still very dizzy after getting to the bed, and showed the infection on her leg.   It had blistered and it was starting to clear.  She was tested to see if she had a stroke and was in the ER for 4-5 hours, and the gave her no treatment, and determined that she was fatigued.  She was having a pain from her rib cage to her right hip that finally went away after 3-4 days.    She went home and was supposed to go feed some friends cows and horses and remembers slipping off the road to the right, and slowed down and then she went home and fed her cows and horses about 4 miles away and then let them back out of the barn.  She did some sweeping, and thought she could hear someone talking through a microphone audio and she could hear him say "what is she doing", and could only hear it in one spot.  She then continued cleaning and then saw the owner of the property coming at her with a woman and a horse and then saw him rubbing a horse and the woman was taking pictures.  She then found out that none of this happened and that she was having hallucinations.  This she found out by talking to the owner who said that  nothing that she thought happened did not.   She went home and was slipping off the road again and realized that she should not be driving on Friday after her ER visit.      On Monday she had the day off and realized that she had been hallucinating on Friday and was talking to her friends.  She went out Monday  night and had dinner with her and tracking her moves.  She was supposed to get the 2nd vaccine, and her friend told her that she should not have the 2nd one, and she was advised by her doctors not to get it.  She then went into the and informed them what happened and they took a report from her.   They told her that she was not hallucinating but lucid dreaming.     Following this she knew that she was okay and trying to figure out if she was hallucinating, and was back to somewhat normal by Tuesday.  She has lost completely of what happened yesterday and has to think about her actions and has to think carefully about what her actions are and that is slowly coming back.  She  used to have a good memory and since the vaccine has to catch what she is supposed to do and feels that this is not her usual and is going to a rehab center and ask for some assistance to get her brain back in gear.   She has to have alarms set to remind her of what she needs to do as she cannot remember what her next steps are.
ALLERGIES: Penicillin's, most antibiotics, Codeine's and Hydrocodone's.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the 2nd COVID vaccine (Pfizer, lot #EW0182 use by 05/22/21 at 10:20) at 1342. Client reported feeling an "itchy" sensation in her throat to EMT at 1356. EMT, immediately notified the Co-lead, RN. RN and other nurse immediately went to assess the client. Patient was allergic to Benadryl so Benadryl was not given.  The patient was in no apparent distress, speaking in full sentences, skin was warm, dry, and intact. Vital signs were taken at 1357, BP- 145/80 (Left arm, sitting upright), HR-81, RR- 17, and oxygen saturation- 99%. Client denied difficulty swallowing, chest pain, shortness of breath, dizziness, lightheadedness, or generalized flushing. Observed the patient's oral mucosa and no swelling, edema, or angioedema was present. The patient stated, " It just feels like phlegm is in my throat, like my saliva is just thicker than normal, and my throat is just a little itchy." The patient was offered Epinephrine, but the patient stated, " No I will hold of on that for now." The patient was also given a bottle of water. Vital signs were taken at 1402, BP- 150/82 (Left arm, sitting upright), HR- 70, RR-17, and oxygen saturation at 100%. The patient was alert and oriented to person, time, place, and situation. The oral cavity was repeatedly observed, no edema or facial swelling was observed. Vitals were retaken at 1407, BP- 150/80 (Left arm, sitting upright), HR- 83, RR- 16, oxygen saturation at 99%. The client denied shortness of breath, chest pain, difficulty breathing. The patient was speaking in full sentences with staff. Vitals were retaken at 1412, BP- 152/ 80 (Left arm, sitting upright), HR- 80, RR- 16, oxygen saturation- 99%.  The patient continued to deny shortness of breath, difficulty swallowing, facial flushing, or chest pain. Vitals were retaken at 1422, BP- 152/70 (Left arm, sitting upright), HR-67, RR-16, oxygen saturation at 100%. The patient stated, " My throat is not as itchy and it just feels like I have thicker phlegm, it feels like what happens when I eat shrimp." RN, offered to call 911 but the client stated, " No I really don't think that is necessary." A final set of vitals was taken at 1427, BP- 150/72 (Left arm, sitting upright), HR- 72, RR- 16, oxygen saturation at 99%. The client had a history of allergic reactions to shrimp, dust, pollen, grass, and codeine. Patient did report being prescribed a Epi-pen in the past but was never able to pick it up from the pharmacy. Client reported going to an allergist in the past for intermittent hives that developed in various regions of her body. Client reported taking Zyrtec every morning, and is diagnosed Bipolar Type II Disorder. The patient reported having a history of anxiety. RN educated the patient about V-Safe and to follow-up with her primary care provider. RN educated the patient about Emergency Room precautions, such as if she experienced shortness of breath, difficulty breathing, chest pain, facial swelling, or altered mental status. The patient had an even and symmetrical gait when leaving the site at 1427.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I immediately felt sharp pain and burning in my arm while being injected. The burning in my arm lasted for about 20 minutes. I got a severe migraine about an hour after the vaccine that lasted for about ten hours.  I broke out in hives all over my body later that night, the same day as the vaccine. I also had intense heartburn. I never get heartburn so this is not normal for me. The following day, I was still having hives and started also having chest pains. I was consistently taking antihistamines to keep the hives under control. On Saturday morning, 2 days after the vaccine, I was still breaking out in hives. My throat also started to swell and I was having a hard time breathing. My heartburn was also getting more severe. I ended up going to urgent care. There I was prescribed 2 stronger antihistamines and prednisone to help with my reaction. I was also given an epi pen.  Later that night, I ended up going to the ER as I was having severe chest pain. I have a history of DVT so I was concerned about blood clots. I had several tests done along with a chest CT scan. Thankfully everything came back clear for blood clots and heart attack. The ER doctor could not explain why I was having chest pain and advised me to monitor it and to come back in if it got worse. The following day, I was still needing antihistamines for hives and difficulty breathing. I woke up in the middle of the night with severe stomach pain and cramping. I had intense vomiting and diarrhea. The diarrhea started to have a lot of blood in it. I went back urgent care and they sent me for a CT scan which showed I now had colitis. The bleeding lasted for about 3 days.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests 2 CT scans Abdominal X Ray

On May 13, 2021, approximately 4 weeks after second dose of the vaccine, I developed a very severe stabbing ice pick headache on the left side of my head behind my eye. By May 17, 2021, the pain was so severe that I went to the emergency room but did not receive a clear diagnosis. On May 18, 2021, I began to notice a prickly sensation on my forehead and rash forming. Urgent care confirmed diagnosis of shingles on evening of May 18, I was prescribed Valtrex, Gabapentin, and an oral steroid. As of today (May 21), the shingles rash is blistering on my left forehead, eyelid, and scalp and is mildly painful, and I have a few swollen lymph nodes, but the shooting nerve headache comes back intermittently and is still very uncomfortable. I feel that this should be reported because if people could be more susceptible to shingles after the vaccine, there should be public information about this. My case was very scary with the terrible shooting nerve pain in my head and I have learned that it is very important to get treatment for shingles started as early as possible to prevent long term effects, so I think this is something people should be made aware of.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On August 29th, 2019 I went to Dr. office for my two year physical for work. The Doctor completed his examination and then told me that I was due for a pneumonia injection. I hesitated and reminded him that I had a serious reaction to the flu shot in 2011 and that was added to my allergy list. He said that the pneumonia vaccine was completely different and I probably would not have a reaction from it.   As soon as I got home from work that night my right upper arm was swollen twice it?s size, very hot to the touch and red in color. I also had a temperature starting which was a little over 100�. I was feeling very ill and went straight to bed. I was sick and very uncomfortable all through the night. When I awoke the next morning on August 30th I called off work because I was so sick I couldn?t get out of bed. My fever had gone up to 102� and I lost use of my right arm. I had to put it in a sling in order to get any comfort. I had no feeling from my elbow up.  As soon as the doctors office opened at 8:00 AM that morning, I called Dr. office and talked to a nurse and told her what my symptoms were. She said that this is quite common for some elderly people to have reactions from certain vaccines and told me to take some ibuprofen and put ice on my upper arm. That was on a Friday and the doctors office was closed over the weekend because it was Labor Day weekend. I suffered all weekend not able to use my right arm and I am right handed. I called the doctors office once again on Tuesday morning, September 3rd. I had an in-service training day on that day but I couldn?t go in because I could not set up or conduct the training at all. I still could not use my right arm.   I talked to a nurse at the doctors office once again that day when they opened at 8 o?clock in the morning and told her that I was still having a very bad reaction. She reminded me to keep taking the ibuprofen and that Dr. did not have any openings until the end of the month but if I continued to react and it caused breathing problems to go to the emergency room. I did not have breathing problems but my arm continued to hurt and is still hurting to this day.  I still cannot lift my right arm above my shoulder without pain. My right shoulder hurts so bad and has been hurting for almost 2 years since the pneumonia injection. I want to scream at times when I have to take my tops or dresses off when I have to pull them off over my head. Sometimes if the neck opening is large enough I pull them down over my body. Many times I?m in tears getting dressed and undressed. I had to adjust my duties at work because I cannot lift children anymore onto the diaper changing station. I was a director at a childcare center and needed to work in different aged classrooms at times. It has interfered with my personal life at home. I can?t reach up to put my dishes away without having a lot of pain. I live on the second floor in my apartment building and carrying up groceries is so painful. I have never had any problems with my arms or shoulders until this pneumonia injection was given to me on August 29th, 2019.   Doctor ordered the MRI on my shoulder. He told me it was possible that I could have inflammation still from receiving that vaccination. I had the MRI on January 23rd, 2020. The reason I was so late getting the MRI was they didn?t have any appointments available until that date.  Because of my position at school, I was covering other classrooms which included very young children. I actually injured my knee twisting it while trying to place a baby down on the rug because I was losing grip with my right arm. So now I have a tear in my lateral meniscus and it has caused fluid to build up behind my kneecap with a cyst. That injury has caused me to be out of work permanently and it is still not better. If my right arm wouldn?t have been injured, I am sure I wouldn?t have lost grip of that child and my knee injury would not have happened.   After Dr. read the MRI results he suggested that I see an Orthopedic doctor ASAP, which I immediately made an appointment. I saw the Orthopedic doctor on Wednesday, January 29th  who?s name is Dr. and he told me that it was possible that the pneumonia injection could have caused the injury to my right shoulder. I actually saw Dr. on January 15 before the MRI. He recommended physical therapy for twice a week which I scheduled at that time.   Unfortunately my torn meniscus on my knee turned into a major situation causing blood clots and I have been in the hospital three times in the last 13 months. I had to stop my therapy for my shoulder and take care of my knee. Dr. did give me a Cortisone injection but it did not help it only lasted about three days and then it went back to hurting again. I have finally started back in March with Physical Therapy and it is improving somewhat if I am consistent. I have seen an orthopedic surgeon Dr., But they cannot do anything more for me because they cannot do surgery. I am on too much blood thinner I am taking Xarelto and Plavix for my lifetime. I do not want any more injections going into that arm. I had to take the Covid injection but they put it in my left arm.
OTHER_MEDS: Methiphenidate 1, 20 mg ER daily Tramadol 50 mg as needed
PRIOR_VAX: Flu Vaccine

3/13 vaccination. 3-4 hours later, I started having symptoms to include tickle in throat, post nasal drip. By 11:40 I had a HA, I was very tired, quite a bit of secretion. I continued taking Benadryl every 3 hours. At 2 :30 PM, heart palpitations and angina. My BP was 98/69. I took more Benadryl, drank some fluids. By 4:15, I was getting drowsy and tired, having pain in multiple joints through my body; 8/10 scale, especially in my hands in feet. I took something for pain. My arm was very sore. I had mild to moderate slight cough. By 7:40 PM I took my regular medication.  I was having a sudden intense HA and pain in joints was 9/10. I was having stiffness, chest congestion, feeling 'flu like' symptoms, brain fog, and weird pains / electro shock pains on extremities. By 830, my symptoms increased to almost a really bad allergic reaction. I couldn't think well, dizzy, cough, chest congestion and my lungs started to hurt. By 10:30pm, I started to have a low grade fever, pain 9/10, I took Ibuprofen and Benadryl every 3 hours.  3/14 Ibuprofen, slight fever, slight HA, joints were swollen and stiff; 8/10 on pain and stiffness. I had muscle pain and brain fog, could not say words. Dull pain back of head. My kidney area, I felt like it hurt, severe anaphylactic reaction it felt like. I still had photophobia. It continued into the evening. I continued taking the Benadryl and ibuprofen. Around 6pm, I had 101.5 temperature, nauseated, crying, chest congestion. By 10:45, my temp was going up again.  Monday I had low grade fever, continued medication. Symptoms continued for a few more days with palpitations, brain fog, pain in lungs and kidneys. I couldn't do anything. By the end of the week, I started to recover.  *My PCM knew before I got the vaccine they were on board and knew what was going to happen in regards to my reaction, EKG, I had epi pen, didn't pass out, I decided I was going to stay home.  *It took me a good couple weeks to recover to my baseline. But it was pretty tough.

I am a nurse practitioner, so as a healthcare worker, I received a very early vaccine. I have had little time to report what happened to me but not that it remains an issue I think I need to do so.  I had a very serious initial reaction and am now having chronic problems likely related to my vaccine. I received my first dose of Moderna 12/27/20 at POD lot# 025J20A and my second dose 1/24/21 at POD lot#029L20A.  After the first vaccine within a few hours I had significant injection site and arm pain. By the time I went to bed that night I could barely lift my arm over my head it was so stiff and warm. The arm was very painful, and I required Ibuprofen 800 mg TID for 3 days to control the pain. I did not have systemic symptoms from the first vaccine. After the second vaccine, within hours I had systemic symptoms of fatigue, generalized aches in my muscles and severe arm pain in the injection arm. I received the vaccine in the afternoon. I went to bed that night and woke up suddenly at 3 am, about 14 hours later. I had severe myalgias and rigors. I was barely able to move. I was not able to walk or perform fine or gross motor tasks without difficulty. I was unable to dress myself or get up to go to the bathroom. I required almost fulltime care from my husband for three days. On day 4 I developed severe headaches nausea and vomiting. The muscles still ached but I was able to walk and move again. My fine motor was still impaired for a total of 7 days. I was out of work for 8 days and did not feel 100% well for 12-14 days after the vaccine. As the symptoms started to resolve on day 5, I believe I had a mild case of Rhabdomyolysis as my urine was very dark almost brown and there was sediment in the toilet. There was no blood in my urine and no dysuria. I did a urine dip at work and it had protein and ketones but no bacteria. The specific gravity was very concentrated. I did not check my renal function at that time. My renal function a few weeks later was normal Cr 0.88. GFR 85. The dark urine and sediment lasted for about 2-3 days. I was drinking lots of water through this time-period and during then I was very ill. I was not seen at a hospital and rather I treated myself at home. During the above week was the first time I ever had neck or back pain. It did subside but I still had a dull aching in my neck after all of this. I had two episodes, one in late January and one in mid-February of left neck being very sensitive to touch, felt warm, and my ear was very hypersensitive to touch as well. It felt almost like shingles but there was never a rash and I took Acyclovir 800 mg TID for 3-5 days without relief. It subsided each time after about 7 days. This was on the same side of my body on the left as the vaccine was. In the end of March 2021 I began with left trapezoid pain in the same side of the body. I had some numbness in that arm as well so I saw orthopedics and received an MRI of my left brachial plexus which showed C3-4, C4-5, and C6-7 disc herniations that had not been present before. If the herniations were present in the past they were acutely inflamed by the inflammatory process the vaccine caused in my body. The MRI also showed significant and specifically left cervical and left axillary adenopathy this being the side of my vaccine. The pain spread beyond my trapezoid and become progressively worse into my neck and upper back only on the left side. The entire left side of my spine both cervical and thoracic was painful but the right side unaffected. It was very sharp nerve like pain shooting and running up into my head and anterior neck. Another MRI was done of the full cervical spine this time confirming these same herniations, but the discs appear to be pulling to the left with isolated left inflammatory process. The nerve pain became so severe that last week I began having numbness in that left arm and numbness into the left side of my face. A stat MRI of my brain only shows T2 flare pattern consistent with sequela of an inflammatory process of unknown origin. The foraminal stenosis at these spinal levels are very mild and do not explain my symptoms very well. Spine specialist reports that there can be symptoms of this nature but usually not with this mild of a pathology. The facial numbness has been identified as a trigeminal neuropathy of cervical origin but is rarely documented in medical journals and not seen by these spine specialists. There is a very significant amount of left sided nerve over stimulation, inflammation and adenopathy that is not explained. I have never had any spine or neck pain in my life before this and I have no history of traumatic events to explain this sudden change in my condition. I truly feel that ever since I received the Moderna vaccine and had that very severe reaction, my body has been in a constant inflammatory phase and there has been nerve pain in and around only the left upper side of my body where the vaccine was placed. I am scheduled on Monday for epidural spinal injections as I have been unable to find pain relief with any other therapies including dry needling, physical therapy, traction, tramadol, muscle relaxers, oral steroid bursts, etc. I know this may be a very strange and unique case, but I can say confidently that I believe the vaccine stimulated this entire cascade of events. If someone could please contact me related to this, I would appreciate it.
OTHER_MEDS: Lamictal  300 mg daily Cymbalta 30 mg daily Zyrtec 10 mg daily Sinuglair 10 mg daily Vitamin D 3,000 iu daily Ambien 10 mg nightly PRN

An hour after receiving the vaccination, I developed a massive lump in my arm, with soreness and redness. Growing concerned I did online research to potentially see what was going on, and following the suggestions from websites- even CDC, I was led to believe that swelling is a normal experience for the vaccination. So a month goes by from the vaccination date, October 23 and the soreness and lump still has not gone down. Still following the advice online, it was suggested that "swelling" can take even up to 3 months to go down. Waiting for the 3 months, it is now January 2021 and I still have the lump in my arm and the arm is still sore, and noticeably more tired and quick to become tired and weak than my right arm, where I have not received the vaccination. At this, I scheduled an appointment at my local clinic to see what is going with my arm. The doctor ordered a Sonagram for my arm.  Even though it was ordered in February, their only  available appointment was in April. Once receiving my sonagram, it was found to have: hypoechoic area in the subcutaneous plane with heterogenous echotexture suggesting complexity. This may be related to a complex seroma versus hematoma. This mass developed after receiving the vaccination- as I did not have this mass nor diagnosis prior to receiving the vaccination.
LAB_DATA: Blood test given, where my absolute neutrophils was found to be low. Was also given a Sonagram to observe and examine mass/lump that developed in my arm.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was nervous about receiving the vaccine, but he was fine after it was administered and sighed with relief. Then he went to our waiting area and about two minutes later he slumped forward into his girlfriend. I ran out there and helped him out of the chair and onto his back on the ground and he immediately felt better.

He received his vaccine, he had a slightly sore arm.  A couple days after the vaccine he was lying in bed and he started out one sentence in jibberish.  He realized that he had done that, paused and apologized to his wife and it happened again in jibberish and he stopped again and he looked at his wife and said "that's not good".  He then found out that the entire time that he was speaking that way, and was aware that he was not making any sense.  The next day he noticed that he was dragging his right foot when he tried to walk.  He made an APT to his doctor and she said that he had a TIA, but the effects had cleared.   The doctor told him to call the cardiologist office and to get an appointment with them, and he saw a cardiologist.  The cardiologist said that he wants him to loose weight and gave him a prescription for Plavix which he is taking.  Ever since he moved to Arizona he has had spontaneous nosebleeds, and have been getting worse every year since being there.  In 2020 they have been the worst that he has had.  He has had nasal cautery twice.  A week after being on the Plavix he had another bleed, and he was advised to stop taking his 81 mg aspirin.  Then a week later still on Plavix he had another nosebleed and this bleed was so bad that he ended up going to UC, and it stopped by the time he got there, and lasted for more than an hour.  He called his cardiologist and his PCP and told them that he was not taking anymore Plavix until the nosebleeds stopped.  He has since then talked to his ENT and told him that the cauterization is not working and is having the nosebleeds of his life.  He suggested that he have surgery for his deviated septum, and has to have clearance from your PCP or cardiologist to have that surgery.   In the past 5 days he has had 3 nosebleeds.  His cardiologist scheduled him a stress test, and also a carotid ultrasound, as well as a CAT scan of his brain and echocardiogram.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, glucosamine chondroitin, Zyrtec, Amlodipine besylate, Lisinopril, Atorvastatin, Melatonin.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer dose 1, lot #EW0182, expiration date 05/22/2021) in his left deltoid at 1425. At 1428, as the pt was walking to the observation area, he was observed falling to the ground. The pt?s girlfriend, protected his head from hitting the ground. EMT staff, Lead RN, and Co-Lead RN responded at 1429. The pt?s girlfriend, told the staff that he was passed out for about 10-15 seconds. Upon arrival from staff, the pt was responsive and alert and oriented x4. The pt denied any pain in his head, difficulty breathing or SOB. Pupils were equal and reactive to light and the client was very diaphoretic (sweaty). At 1430, vital signs were BP: 122/58, P: 55, O2: 97%, and RR: 20. The pt denied history of seizures, any other medical history, allergies and takes no medications. The pt stated ?I am afraid of needles but have never fainted after a vaccine or blood draw?. The pt mentioned the last time he ate was breakfast at 0930. At 1435, the pt no longer felt dizzy or lightheaded and walked over to the observation area to sit in the anti-gravity chair. At 1435, the pt finished a granola bar and juice. Vital signs were taken again at 1445, BP: 128/75, P: 85, O2: 98%, and RR: 16. Lead RN and Co-Lead RN educated the pt on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Pt was also educated on sitting in the anti-gravity chair for his second dose of Pfizer. Pt left facility at 1447 walking with a steady gait with girlfriend, pt?s mother picked them up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The following is transcribed from a report submitted by Paramedic on a 72 yo female who received 2nd Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot# EN 6203, exp 6/2021) in right arm at approx 10:45am: "At 10:45am, I observed an elderly female with increased respiratory effort, flushed skin, appearing to be in mild distress, sitting in the 15 min. observation area. I approached patient and asked if she was doing okay, and she stated "yes." Patient's skin was flushed, diaphoretic, and warm. Pupils equal and sluggish. Patient denied any other complaints but claims she felt lightheaded prior to vaccine. Patient was moved to 30 min. observation. Patient was able to stand up and ambulate without assistance. EMTs took vital signs as another patient arrived. 11:05am baseline vital signs obtained: blood pressure 124/80, respiratory rate 16, heart rate 100, alert and oriented to person, time, place, and situation. At 11:12am, patient's vital signs were re-assessed and radial pulse palpated which was strong, regular with occasional PVC's felt. Blood pressure 130/82, respiratory rate 16, heart rate 108, alert and oriented to person, time, place and situation. C/C reassessed and she reported no change. It was advised that due to her physical appearance not improving with skin flushed and diaphoretic, ALS would be contacted to further evaluate; patient obliged. At 11:27am 911 contact made with a 6 minute response time with fire department on scene. Patient turnover report given and care transferred. Patient AMA'd (left against medical advice) with fire department. Patient ambulated with steady gait and without assistance.

Patient is a 58-year-old, female. Alert, oriented X4, clear speech, able to answer to questions. No known medical conditions. History of allergies to Hydrocodone. At 9:25 am, patient notified EMT that she was experiencing lightheadedness, dizziness, nausea and ringing in ears. EMT gave patient emesis bag and began taking patient's vitals. Patient remained A&Ox4 and talking to EMT. At 9:27 am: BP of 122/70, HR 71, SPO2 99%. EMT reclined patient in chair and encouraged deep breathing. At 9:35 am: BP 124/74, SPO2 99%, HR 71. Patient states she had a light breakfast, so EMT offered patient a snack. Patient consumed 1 granola bar. Patient states she experienced ringing in ears for approximately 2 weeks following her first dose. Patient did not seek medical treatment. RN provided patient with education related to adverse reactions to vaccine. RN recommended patient talk to PCP about persistent ringing in ears. At 9:48 am: BP 122/80, SPO2 99%, HR 76. At 9:52 am, patient reports slight ringing in ears. Patient denies headache. Patient still experiencing "slight" dizziness. Patient requesting to leave site at 9:55 am. Lead RN provided patient with education concerning when to call 9-1-1, including worsening of symptoms and trouble breathing. Patient was instructed to follow up with PCP. At 9:56 am, patient walked to car with steady, balanced gait.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This patient was brought into the Medical Center COVID-19 vaccine clinic by his mother for vaccination.  The patient is 16 years old.  At the time of this incident, medical center provides only the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine at this clinic.  Moderna COVID-19 vaccine is only approved under for patients over the age of 18 years old under the EUA in effect at the time of this occurrence.  Prior to the event, the patient was registered into the medical center system in the presence, and with the consent of the patient's mother.  The hospital registration staff failed to recognize how the patient's age of 16 years is a contraindication to Moderna COVID-19 vaccination.   The patient was next brought to a COVID-19 task force medic. Task force failed to recognize the patient's age as 16 years old, despite how the patient's age was displayed on the electronic health record (EHR) screen.  This information  displayed in the same vaccination menu where task force documented the shot.  They commenced to vaccinate the patient in his right deltoid with one Moderna COVID-19 vaccination dose; 0.5 ml in volume via intramuscular injection.    Immediately after vaccinating the patient, task force was unable to complete the documentation in the EHR system.  He notified me of the issue.  When I looked at the screen, I noticed that the patient displayed an age of only 16 years.  I asked him if he had already vaccinated the patient.  He replied, "yes" he had.    Upon discovering this event, I immediately contacted the patient's mother and informed her of the incident.  Then, I called my chain-of-command in the COVID-19 task force and briefed the officer in charge of the incident.  The COVID-19 Task Force officer instructed me to complete this VAERS report.  I also informed the medical center manager on site of the incident. Medical center staff on site immediately reported the incident via their internal risk management reporting system in addition to this VAERS report.
LAB_DATA: Patient remained in the vaccine clinic's observation area under the care of a registered nurse for 45 minutes.  During the time of observation, the patient did not report any complaints.  No tests or labs were ordered at this time.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient's mother denies patient uses any of these substances.
CUR_ILL: Patient's mother denies patient has any illnesses within specified time frame.
HISTORY: Patient's mother denies patient has any chronic health conditions.
ALLERGIES: Patient's mother denies patient has any known allergies.

May 8: In the mid-afternoon I developed a blister on my right elbow at an outdoor gathering. It did not hurt. I thought I had perhaps been bitten by a bug. Once the blister burst it was moderately painful, and it has been slow to heal (I still have the scab). I don't think it's related (wrong side of the body, appeared before the back pain, etc.) but only mention it because it was similar in appearance to the first large blister on my left breast (except smaller, maybe 1/3 the size), and that is why I initially brushed off the blistering. May 12: I began having intermittent back pain between my left shoulder blade and my spine. I had fallen off our hammock the day before and attributed the back pain to that.  May 13: I woke up with a large (1.5") blister on the left (outer) side of my left breast. I often sleep with a heating pad, and thought that I must have burned myself. However, I found it strange that it did not hurt at all. I thought perhaps I had touched a poisonous plant while gardening, and had then touched my breast putting my phone in my bra, or something. I even thought it was maybe a weird spider bite. None of these seemed to fit because the area didn't hurt.  May 14: the back pain continued intermittently and I took naproxen sodium to control the pain. The blister remained painless. May 15: It was hot that day (80 degrees) and we went to a local garden and did a lot of walking around. When I got home that night I had a slightly irritated patch of skin on my left side - right at the level of my bra strap and I assumed I had heat rash. The bumps were surprisingly tender, but not connected (stand alone little dots). My back pain had worsened - it was hard to pick up and hold my children, it was tender from the walk, and I kept on a strict schedule of naproxen sodium every 8 hours to try to control the pain. May 16: It was hot again and we went to a couple more local gardens and walked around. My back pain was pretty bad, but manageable when I wasn't carrying the kids. At the end of the day when I got home I saw that the "heat rash" had spread in a line under my left breast. It was now very tender to the touch, but felt fine if you left it alone. I was concerned that I had some sort of breast inflammation, and again, did not connect it to the back pain. May 17: My back pain was unmanageable, and I had to take several breaks from work to lie down. In the evening I discovered that the small dots on my left side were not pimples/ irritated skin, but rather tiny individual blisters. After looking into it more, I thought that I possibly had shingles since I had had chickenpox as a kid. May 18: My sleep was interrupted by the bad back pain, and I woke up several times. When I woke up the rash had spread to my sternum, and around my side onto my back. It was incredibly painful to the touch, and instead of being standalone dots there was now red inflammation connecting the blisters. My back pain was incredibly bad. I called and tried to get an appointment to see my doctor, but could not get scheduled until the morning of May 19. May 19: Did not sleep well due to pain. Doctor performed a visual exam of the inflammation and listened to the symptoms and diagnosed me with shingles with complications (the nerve pain). I had two pin prick red dots on my left wrist, and one itchy red bump on my left leg and I was concerned that it was spreading to other areas of my body. Prescribed the retroviral valacyclovir 1 g three times/ day for 7 days to try to reduce the length and severity of the illness, but advised that I had started treatment "too late" since I had not realized I had shingles and was past the 72 hour window so it may be less effective. Prescribed gabapentin 300 mg three times/ day for 7 days for nerve pain. Recommended using lidocaine and capsaicin cream 3 times/ day, too. I started treatment with all 4 of these right away. Dr. also advised me that she did not think the shingles were per se caused by the covid vaccine, but because it appeared in close proximity to my dose #2 (and I had side effects for several days indicating a strong immune response) that I should report it to the CDC just in case - which is why I am filing this report.  May 20: Rash on my back continued to spread all the way to my spine. Rash on chest worsened/ turned bright red. Back pain was extreme and not controlled by gabapentin. Pin pricks on wrist never turned itchy/ into blisters - I think they actually were heat rash from my watch. Bump on my left ankle appears to be a bug bite. I started getting periodic (every hour or two) sharp pains in my left ear, but no tinnitus. Periodic sharp pains in left side, left shoulder, and along my spine. Constant deep ache along my spine, and tenderness on my left side. Extremely fatigued. Taking gapapentin, valacyclovir 3x/day, and administers capzacin cream + a lidocane patch for areas of pain that do not have open wounds. May 21: For the first time the rash appears to be the same, or maybe even slightly improved from last night in terms of appearance. The back pain and skin tenderness is the same. Ear pain is more frequent - almost like I have an ear infection, with periodic sharp jabs multiple times an hour, but no tinnitus. Taking gapapentin, valacyclovir 3x/day, and administers capzacin cream + a lidocane patch for areas of pain that do not have open wounds.
LAB_DATA: May 19: Visual exam/ medical history/ diagnosis, I have a follow-up appointment on May 24 to assess how well I'm responding to treatment, and potentially extend the valacyclovir, gabapentin, or both.

About a week and a half after receiving the first and only dose of the Johnson and Johnson Covid-19 vaccine, I developed small bruises (Petechiae) on my chest and arm. I decided to consult my doctor just in case. My doctor did a blood draw and ran a CBC panel. The next day I was rushed to the ER as my platelet count was reported at 7. By the time I got to the ER my platelets had dropped even further to a count of 2. I was treated inpatient for 3 days 2 nights. At this time I was diagnosed with IPT (Immune Thrombocytopenia Purpura). It was treated with two rounds of IVIG (Intravenous immunoglobulin) and 75 mg of Prednisone daily (which I have been slowly tapering off of since). My platelets restored to a non-critical level and have continued to hold steady ever since.
LAB_DATA: CBC Panel- April 22nd, 2021- platelet count of 7,000

Patient came to conference room shortly after receiving her first dose of the Pfizer vaccine with complaints of tingling in her face and said she felt like she was going to pass out. She denied chest pain, shortness of breath or difficulty swallowing. She was alert to time, place, and event. Her skin was normal color and warm to touch. Upon questioning her she said she was nervous about getting the vaccine and had only had coffee this morning, but nothing to eat. Staff began obtaining her first set of vital signs and asking about medical history. She denied diabetes but said she did have high blood pressure but did not take medication (she said her normal BP was 140s/85-95). We gave her water and saltine crackers to see if her symptoms would resolve. After a few minutes she said she was still having the same feelings, though they had not gotten worse. At this time I checked her vital signs and conferred with staff. We encouraged her to seek further treatment and be transported to the emergency department via EMS. Patient refused ambulance and said she would have her husband drive her (he was in the room with us at this time and agreed to take her to local emergency department). We transported patient to her vehicle via wheelchair. Staff called ED and gave report of these events to one of the ED nurses. I told her husband we would reach out later today to follow up with the situation.
LAB_DATA: 2 sets of vital signs were taken. 1 at 0908: heart rate 90 BPM, RR 17, BP 200/120 manual, PO2 94%.  2nd set at 0915: heart rate 97 BPM, RR 17, BP 200/110 manual, PO2 98%
ALLERGIES: no known food or drug allergies

Within 2 days, the lymph nodes at my collar bone/neck on the left side began to swell. By the following Tuesday, I went to the ER for the enlargement. Routine blood tests showed nothing unusual (lymphoma). Was sent home to see my doctor if the swelling doesn't subside.  Scheduled an appointment with my PCM on 23 Apr 2021 (virtual - they are not seeing in-person patients yet). By this point, the swelling had not subsided and there was new pain in my left elbow shooting dow nto my hand.  The doctor prescribed Naprosyn, lidocaine patches, and a wrist brace to keep the nerves stable. Was told it was "pain management" until the swelling from the lymph nodes go down. It is now 6 weeks post-vaccine and the pain and swelling is still the same. I have been unable to secure an appointment with my PCM. For the past 6 weeks, my pain level has been at a steady 8 out 10.
LAB_DATA: The only lab tests conducted were at the ER to ensure I did not have any markers for lymphoma (parent died from lymphoma).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient and Patient Mother denied that patient had any history of fainting or dizziness with needle puncture. Patient was administered First dose of Pfizer vaccine 11:23am. Patient was seated in observation area with mother and sibling at 11:24am. At 11:25 am patient began to verbalize that vision was disturbed and mother notified staff who informed me. When I approached patient the patients eyes were closed and patient was unconscious and unresponsive. I administered a sternal rub and patient opened eyes and tried to speak but sounded slurred. Patient was unconscious for less than ten seconds. At 11:27am patient was able to answer all LOC questions appropriately and community health worker was instructed to get Wheel chair. Patient was able to help with transfer and patient was placed in wheel chair with minimal effort. At 11:28 Patient was taken to room 8 with recliner chair. Patient was placed in recliner with minimal assistance with legs raised and patient was given water which patient sipped. Pt was encouraged to rest and patient closed eyes and laid head back. At 11:32 am Vital signs machine was unable to be used  due to power outage so E-cart had to be opened to remove stethoscope and BP cuff. At 11:34 am Vitals signs were taken: BP-92/57 HR: 65 RR: 16 and patient denied any lightheadedness, dizziness, or fainting feeling. Pt requested to have mask off during observation. Patient and patient mother were instructed that a thirty minute wait time would be recommended and both verbalized understanding. MD was not notified since patient was talking appropriately and vision disturbance was resolving. Mother agreed that because patient condition was improving, that there was no need to involve MD. Patient continued to sip water and rest. Patient continued to close eyes periodically but began to keep eyes opened longer. At 11:46 am patient stated ?I feel a little tired, but I feel better.? Vital signs were taken: BP- 96/59 HR:65 RR:16 and patient denied any symptoms. At 11:53 a Patient stated felt well enough to leave. Patient was instructed to stand up and stay standing for a few seconds to ensure patient did not become dizzy. Patient was able to walk around the room with no gait or stability issues. Patient and patient mother were instructed to relay this occurrence to RN for second Dose of Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine to ensure that staff can take the proper safety precautions. Patient and patient mother verbalized understanding. Patient left with mother and sibling awake and oriented x4 with no issues.

Monday May 17th Mild headache Mild fatigue Mild nausea  Tuesday May 18th I was feeling ok with only mlid fatigue then later in the afternoon my heart started fluttering.  My pulse kept dropping into the 40's then going high into the 120's.  I was having chest pain's and my blood pressure was higher than normal.  My oxygen level was good.  Around 10pm my husband brought me to the emergency room.  My BP was 181/98 when I arrived.  They did an EKG immediately and said I had multiple PVC's. They started me on heparin and admitted me.    May 19th I was in the hospital and experienced a moderate headache and nausea.  They continued the heparin and IV fluids and also gave me potassium. The PVC's continued but were less frequent.  May 20th I was discharged from the hospital later in the day.  I had a moderate headache and moderate nausea.  The PVC's continued but less frequent.  May 21st Moderate headache Moderate fatigue Moderate nausea I'm not thinking clearly and I'm having troubles concentrating. Starting approximately one week after vaccination I started to experience onset of loud  tinnitus primarily in my left ear. I have experienced mild tinnitus for 8 years but this was much more severe. The night of 04/19/2021 I noticed the onset of dizziness which progressed to strong vertigo the morning of the 20th. It was so severe I was unable to work and stayed in bed for the better part of two days. It was accompanied by the increased tinnitus.   I scheduled an appt with my primary care physician for 04/23 and by Thursday 04/22 the vertigo had decreased to a general dizziness with tinnitus in my left ear.  Dr prescribed Meclizine 25mg to me which has not appreciably addressed the symptom which as of 05/21 continues to be a constant mild dizziness with pronounced tinnitus in my left ear. I am planning to see an ENT that specializes in AIED (auto immune inner ear disorder) which I suspect was triggered my my immune system response to the vaccine.   I should note that 8 years earlier I had a milder but similar case of vertigo w tinnitus which was never diagnosed despite extensive testing (vestibular migraine as a diagnosis by exclusion). It gradually subsided over 2 years with only mild tinnitus remaining as a symptom.

Client  received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer dose 1, lot #EW0185, expiration date5/2/2021) at 1536 in her left arm. The client reported "my heart is going fast and slow" and 1550. EMTs, and RN responded at that time. The client endorsed "pressure" in her chest nausea, and some shortness of breath. The client's vital signs were as follows: heart rate 110, O2 99%, respiratory rate 20, blood pressure 138/118. The client's skin was pink, warm, and dry, and she was alert and oriented. The client stated her shortness of breath was getting worse and 911 was called at 1554. Per the client, she has no history of needle anxiety or syncope. She stated that she did eat lunch prior to getting her vaccine. The client stated that she has a medical history of SVT (supraventricular tachycardia) and she does take medication for it but she did not remember the name ("it sounds like lisinopril", "it works like a beta blocker") and she hadn't taken the medication today. The client has an allergy to morphine. At 1556, the client's vital signs were as follows: heart rate 116, blood pressure 128/palpable, and O2 98. The client stated they don't have a previous history of anxiety. The client was observed to be sitting forward in their chair, with increased work of breathing, and visible diaphoresis. The client stated they had a sudden onset headache and rated the pain 6/10. The client stated they have no history of migraines and have "never had a headache like this before." The client dry heaved repeatedly and complained of persistent nausea, as well as "twisting" pain in her left axilla. The client's pulse was bounding and she endorsed changes in her vision. Pupils were equal and reactive to light. The client continued to be alert and oriented, but very anxious. She was able to demonstrate equal strength in hand grips. AMR arrived and assumed care at 1600. Client transported to Hospital at 1607.

After the vaccine, patient felt fine and was moved to our waiting area.  Within 5 minutes of being seated, patient fell out of the chair and hit his head.  The person he was with asked for our help.  When my intern and I approached him, he was awake and alert.  He said he just passed out.  He did have a bump on his head.  I went to get ice and when I came back my intern noticed he was more pale and disoriented.  Within a minute or so, patient was more alert and we were able to take his BP/HR.  His HR was low but patient confirmed he has a low resting heart rate.  His BP was elevated slightly (around 145/75, HR 59).  He was still pale and sweating so we kept talking to the patient and got him more water.  We checked his BP again and it was about the same but patient was feeling better.   Patient denies having had this reaction before from any vaccine or medication.   He later said that he sometimes gets nervous when he gets the flu shot so it could have been him psyching himself out.  We kept monitoring patient and after about 45-60 minutes, patient left and had someone drive him home to be on the safe side.  Patient denies having any primary care md.  I called him around 726pm and patient said he was stable and took some Motrin and felt fine. He will contact us if anything changes.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Adverse event: PT abruptly felt lightheaded approximately 14 minutes after receiving Moderna COVID vaccine at 1235. PT lowered herself to the floor to lay on her left side. PT presented with pallor and diaphoresis. RN responding called for aid at 1249, aid arrived at 1251. SPO2 was 97% on RA. PT reported a history of syncope, especially after injections, denies significant medical history and was unsure of baseline BP. EMTs prompted PT to sit in chair, PT was able to rise without difficulty, but continued to c/o 'lightheadedness'. EMTs provided education on vaso-vagal response, provided juice and water to PT. PT reported feeling "stable, but a little warm" and then reported increasing nausea. PT provided emesis bag and chose to lay down once again, reporting that she felt better laying down. At 1304,  PT reported that her nausea was resolved, and that she felt 'normal'. Denied vision changes, vertigo when moving head side to side. Color improved. EMTs medically cleared PT at 1313 to be driven home by husband.  Treatment: Juice and water were provided, EMTs assessed/treated (Vitals at 1250: Bp 100/P laying, HR 106, SPO2 97% RA. 1255: BP 100/P sitting, HR 92, SPO2 99% RA. 1303: BP 96/52 laying. 1308: BP 102/60 sitting). Pupil check at 1300 WNL, PT declined CBG check. Education provided on s/s to watch for, when to seek medical care provided by RN. Outcome: PT was medically cleared by EMTs at 1313, driven home in private vehicle by husband. HCP Responding: RN, EMT, EMT, RN
PRIOR_VAX: Unknown, syncope reaction

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This injection caused frozen shoulder. The pain started the same day and I assumed it was normal to have pain at the injection site. The pain got worse and worse and never resolved.  I thought about having the second shot done on the right shoulder since the left side soreness never went away. But I had in on the left side and although it got sore, that soreness from the second shot dissipated in two days. The soreness from the first shot still hadn't resolved and the shoulder had started losing ROM after the first injection but I didn't really notice until it became "frozen" and very painful in March.  I have been seeing a chiropractor, acupuncturist and saw an orthopedic doctor. I am scheduled to start PT in 2 weeks. It is still very painful and very limited ROM.  I am hoping this isn't a permanent disability because this started right after the injection in January and here we are in May!
LAB_DATA: Orthopedic doctor did an x-ray and orthopedic tests in his office and confirmed the diagnosis of adhesive capsulitis (frozen shoulder)

Patient preferred to transfer care to outpatient rehab service closer to home with more social support.  Repeat hospitalized 3 weeks later, less extreme, went back to ER, stroke eval neg.
